Reading a scenario question, and the distractor patterns.

S-A-A questions are paragraphs, not one-liners, and a repeatable reading pattern turns time into accuracy. First, find the verb. You need to ensure, provide, minimise, or prevent something; that's the goal, so skim past the setup until you've found it. Second, highlight the constraints, least operational overhead, most cost-effective, minimum downtime, no public I-P, across two Regions; each constraint eliminates options. Third, match the constraint to a service, not to a feature: global, edge-cached, with W-A-F means CloudFront; reliable, in-order processing means S-Q-S FIFO, not Standard and not S-N-S. And fourth, eliminate by capability mismatch: if an option simply cannot do what's asked, a Classic Load Balancer has no host-based routing, DynamoDB has no S-Q-L joins, strike it, and usually two of the four fall away immediately.

Now the recurring distractor patterns. When it says minimum operational overhead, pick the managed service, Lambda over E-C-2, Fargate over self-managed E-C-S, Aurora Serverless over Postgres on E-C-2. When it says encrypt data at rest with a customer-managed key, that's a K-M-S C-M-K, not the A-W-S-managed default. When it says most cost-effective plus infrequent access, that's usually S3 Standard-Infrequent-Access or Glacier, and you check the first-byte latency tolerance to pick which. Classic Load Balancer, NAT instance, and E-C-2-Classic are usually wrong answers in modern questions; A-L-B, NAT Gateway, and V-P-C are the modern primitives. And Multi-A-Z versus read replica: Multi-A-Z is for failover, not read scaling, while read replicas are for read scaling, not automatic failover; a question that says increase read throughput wants read replicas. The meta-skill: the exam rewards elimination over recall. You rarely need the one perfect fact; you need to strike the two options that violate a stated constraint, then choose between the survivors on the explicit preference.
